00:43:29.699 --> 00:43:34.179
just really learning everything there is to know about education, training, and assessments,

00:43:35.219 --> 00:43:43.139
and honestly, I had a mutual friend who was having trouble

00:43:45.459 --> 00:43:48.979
finding out how to learn about data and how to learn. Specifically, actually, it was our

00:43:48.979 --> 00:43:54.340
programming. He was an analyst on Wall Street who spent most of his time in Excel, and a friend of

00:43:54.340 --> 00:43:59.219
his showed him how he could automate literally three weeks of work into an afternoon,

00:44:00.020 --> 00:44:06.500
so he saw the value of that, and then when I was in my career, I also was using some data-driven

00:44:06.500 --> 00:44:11.620
methods, but I couldn't find any resources that were specific to me as a professional where I

00:44:11.620 --> 00:44:17.379
could just pick it up quickly, so we had a conversation and thought, well, if we can't

00:44:17.379 --> 00:44:25.939
find what we need, let's build it, so it was myself and then two other co-founders, and

00:44:28.979 --> 00:44:34.260
I said that the best thing that happens is that we still have a company and we build something

00:44:34.260 --> 00:44:39.540
cool, and the worst thing that happens is that I learn a lot, and I did quit my job nine months

00:44:39.540 --> 00:44:46.500
into it, and I said, well, I can always go find another job, and so along the way, I learned data

00:44:46.500 --> 00:44:52.979
science, and I found it to be really empowering. I've never programmed before, and to understand

00:44:52.979 --> 00:45:00.820
how it works, to understand how it can be impactful for folks, and then building something was really

00:45:00.820 --> 00:45:06.820
fun for me, so I just love solving challenges, and this was definitely a lot of challenges to solve.

00:45:10.179 --> 00:45:14.899
That's great. I don't think I see other side of the question, so I do want to open it up

00:45:14.899 --> 00:45:19.459
to a broader discussion, and I can stop the recording, but I had one question, too.

00:45:20.419 --> 00:45:27.459
I was curious, have you ever been in a position where you're not able to make the case to

00:45:28.659 --> 00:45:34.260
leadership, or they're pushing back on you, and what do you do in that situation?

00:45:36.500 --> 00:45:42.179
We do get a lot of pushback. Interestingly enough, what I would say is it's not always

00:45:42.179 --> 00:45:49.780
talked to your leadership. A lot of times, it's management folks that have been doing

00:45:49.780 --> 00:45:56.340
this for a while. You don't really see a need to change. There are a few points that I bring up

00:45:56.340 --> 00:46:05.540
that I think are particularly effective. The first one is it's not something, let's say, that we're

00:46:05.540 --> 00:46:10.020
forcing you to do tomorrow. We're not going to shift everything that you're doing. We're not

00:46:10.020 --> 00:46:14.659
saying that what you're doing is wrong. What we're doing is showing you a different set of

00:46:14.659 --> 00:46:20.419
tools and a different set of skills that might make your life easier, so by alleviating the

00:46:20.419 --> 00:46:26.659
type of pressure of being forced to implement this, you're giving people room to explore and

00:46:26.659 --> 00:46:32.979
understand for themselves why it's important, and sometimes it might not be. If there's a system

00:46:32.979 --> 00:46:39.300
that works well within an organization, you don't need more out of it. It's fine. I'm not going to

00:46:39.300 --> 00:46:47.060
force somebody to implement something in R if it's working just fine in Excel, so it's important

00:46:47.060 --> 00:46:54.500
to have that mindset. I think the second point is, and again, it depends on the level that you're

00:46:54.500 --> 00:47:01.540
speaking to. It will be really, really hard to stay competitive without these skills, just period.

00:47:02.500 --> 00:47:08.340
There are organizations that are becoming really data-driven. There are organizations that are

00:47:08.340 --> 00:47:14.340
leveraging their data very, very effectively, and that translates to increased profits, increased

00:47:14.340 --> 00:47:21.860
revenue, increased efficiency, more satisfaction, increased retention of employees, and guess what?

00:47:21.860 --> 00:47:26.500
If you're competing against that organization in five years and you don't have that same level of

00:47:26.500 --> 00:47:33.620
skills, you're going to be feeling it, and so bringing in an element of, hey, here are what

00:47:33.620 --> 00:47:42.500
the best practitioners are doing in your industry, and so if you're not driving towards that,

00:47:43.379 --> 00:47:48.979
just be aware. It's going to be harder to stay competitive. It really is a business necessity,

00:47:50.979 --> 00:47:58.739
and then the third one is finding any type of successful project or any type of

00:47:59.540 --> 00:48:06.179
use case that will speak to that audience, so whenever I give my presentations, I like to

00:48:06.179 --> 00:48:15.219
pull from different use cases in an industry where people can relate to, and I find that

00:48:15.219 --> 00:48:20.419
that really helps with the light bulb moment because they start to understand how they could

00:48:20.419 --> 00:48:26.580
be doing something similar, so those are three points that I would recommend. It doesn't always

00:48:26.580 --> 00:48:35.219
work. It really does depend where the organization is, their budget. If somebody's

00:48:35.219 --> 00:48:41.459
invested like 10 million dollars in a tool, they're going to want to use that tool

00:48:41.459 --> 00:48:46.580
whether it's helpful or not, so there are some things that are harder to get around.

00:48:46.580 --> 00:48:54.179
Definitely. Thank you, and I want to stay true to what I said where I'll stop the recording

